      <%// ─── DETAIL: GITOPS ──────────────────────────────────── %>
      <div purpose="detail-section" id="gitops">
        <div purpose="detail-heading">
          <h4>GitOps and CI/CD</h4>
          <h3>Manage device configuration the way you manage code</h3>
          <p>Store Fleet configuration in Git. Review every change as a pull request, deploy through CI/CD, and roll back instantly when something goes wrong.</p>
        </div>
        <div purpose="detail-vendors">
          <span class="vendor-tag">GitHub Actions</span>
          <span class="vendor-tag">GitLab CI</span>
          <span class="vendor-tag">fleetctl CLI</span>
        </div>
        <div purpose="detail-grid">
          <div purpose="use-cases">
            <p purpose="detail-subheading">Top use cases</p>
            <div purpose="use-case"><span purpose="use-case-num">1</span><p><strong>Peer-reviewed device changes.</strong> All config changes go through pull requests so teammates can review before changes reach devices.</p></div>
            <div purpose="use-case"><span purpose="use-case-num">2</span><p><strong>Instant rollback.</strong> Revert a Git commit and re-run the pipeline. Fleet applies the previous known-good configuration.</p></div>
            <div purpose="use-case"><span purpose="use-case-num">3</span><p><strong>Audit trail for compliance.</strong> Git history provides an immutable record of who changed what, when, and why.</p></div>
          </div>
          <div purpose="how-it-works">
            <p purpose="detail-subheading">How it works</p>
            <div purpose="how-step"><span purpose="how-dot"></span><p>Define policies, queries, MDM profiles, and software packages as YAML files in a Git repo.</p></div>
            <div purpose="how-step"><span purpose="how-dot"></span><p>GitHub Actions or GitLab CI runs <code>fleetctl gitops</code> on merge to apply changes to Fleet.</p></div>
            <div purpose="how-step"><span purpose="how-dot"></span><p>Fleet validates the configuration and rolls it out to targeted hosts, with full version history.</p></div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <a purpose="back-to-overview" href="#stack-hub">Back to overview</a>
      </div>


      <%// ─── DETAIL: SIEM ────────────────────────────────────── %>
      <div purpose="detail-section" id="siem">
        <div purpose="detail-heading">
          <h4>SIEM and data lakes</h4>
          <h3>Feed real-time endpoint data into your security stack</h3>
          <p>Stream Fleet logs, osquery results, and vulnerability data into your SIEM or data lake so security teams can correlate endpoint telemetry with network, cloud, and identity events in one place.</p>
        </div>
        <div purpose="detail-vendors">
          <span class="vendor-tag">Splunk</span>
          <span class="vendor-tag">Snowflake</span>
          <span class="vendor-tag">Elastic</span>
          <span class="vendor-tag">Google Chronicle</span>
          <span class="vendor-tag">Kinesis, Firehose, Kafka, PubSub</span>
        </div>
        <div purpose="detail-grid">
          <div purpose="use-cases">
            <p purpose="detail-subheading">Top use cases</p>
            <div purpose="use-case"><span purpose="use-case-num">1</span><p><strong>Threat detection and correlation.</strong> Ingest osquery results to build detections that combine endpoint, network, and identity signals.</p></div>
            <div purpose="use-case"><span purpose="use-case-num">2</span><p><strong>Vulnerability analytics at scale.</strong> Stream CVE data to Snowflake to build dashboards covering vulnerability trends, patch SLAs, and risk by business unit.</p></div>
            <div purpose="use-case"><span purpose="use-case-num">3</span><p><strong>Incident investigation.</strong> Search historical endpoint data to reconstruct timelines during incident response.</p></div>
          </div>
          <div purpose="how-it-works">
            <p purpose="detail-subheading">How it works</p>
            <div purpose="how-step"><span purpose="how-dot"></span><p>Configure Fleet log destinations to ship osquery results, host status, and CVE data using Firehose, Kinesis, Kafka, or PubSub.</p></div>
            <div purpose="how-step"><span purpose="how-dot"></span><p>Land the data in Splunk, Snowflake, Elastic, Chronicle, or any data lake downstream.</p></div>
            <div purpose="how-step"><span purpose="how-dot"></span><p>Build dashboards, alerts, and detection rules alongside the rest of your security telemetry.</p></div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <a purpose="back-to-overview" href="#stack-hub">Back to overview</a>
      </div>


