        <div purpose="detail-grid">
          <div purpose="use-cases">
            <p purpose="detail-subheading">Top use cases</p>
            <div purpose="use-case"><span purpose="use-case-num">1</span><p><strong>Detect drift, automate remediation.</strong> Fleet identifies drifted hosts. Ansible, Puppet, or Chef playbooks converge the device back to desired state.</p></div>
            <div purpose="use-case"><span purpose="use-case-num">2</span><p><strong>Deploy Fleet agents at scale.</strong> Use your existing CM tool to push and manage the fleetd agent across thousands of servers and workstations.</p></div>
            <div purpose="use-case"><span purpose="use-case-num">3</span><p><strong>Verify compliance after changes.</strong> After a Chef or Puppet run, use Fleet queries to confirm the change took effect.</p></div>
          </div>
          <div purpose="how-it-works">
            <p purpose="detail-subheading">How it works</p>
            <div purpose="how-step"><span purpose="how-dot"></span><p>Fleet runs scheduled queries and policies to continuously monitor device state across your infrastructure.</p></div>
            <div purpose="how-step"><span purpose="how-dot"></span><p>Policy failures fire webhooks to your CM tool or SOAR, kicking off remediation playbooks.</p></div>
            <div purpose="how-step"><span purpose="how-dot"></span><p>CM tools deploy <code>fleetd</code> through their package workflows (cookbooks, playbooks, manifests).</p></div>
